8 POLICY COMMITTEE RECOMMENDATION
9 An Act relating to criminal procedure; amending 22
O.S. 2021, Sections 1175.1, as last amended by
10 Section 1, Chapter 364, O.S.L. 2025, 1175.3, as
amended by Section 2, Chapter 73, O.S.L. 2024,
11 1175.4, as amended by Section 3, Chapter 73, O.S.L.
2024, 1175.7 and 1175.8 (22 O.S. Supp. 2025, Sections
12 1175.1, 1175.3 and 1175.4), which relate to
competency determinations; updating name of forensic
13 examiners; providing for evaluations of individuals
rather than examinations; providing procedures for
14 determining appropriate treatment for persons found
incompetent and committed to the Department of Mental
15 Health and Substance Abuse Services; requiring
individuals to consent and comply with certain terms
16 and conditions when participating in community-based
outpatient competency restoration programs; directing
17 providers to submit reports concerning compliance or
violations; allowing modification of court orders
18 under certain circumstances; providing for inpatient
care when necessary; authorizing participating
19 individuals to receive additional treatment or
support services; prohibiting courts from committing
20 persons who are currently serving active sentences;
providing an exception; making provisions applicable
21 regardless of when criminal sentencing occurred;
providing conflict of laws provision; providing for
22 the appointment of medical supervisors under certain
circumstances; allowing for inpatient or outpatient
23 treatment; requiring periodic progress reports to the
court; authorizing payment of services from court
24 funds; permitting the use of private treatment
Req. No. 16517 Page 1

1 facilities; directing courts to conduct additional
competency hearings within certain number of days
2 after receiving reports of competency; and providing
an effective date.
3
4
5
6
7 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
8 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 22 O.S. 2021, Section 1175.1, as
9 last amended by Section 1, Chapter 364, O.S.L. 2025 (22 O.S. Supp.
10 2025, Section 1175.1), is amended to read as follows:
11 Section 1175.1. As used in Sections 1175.1 through 1176 of this
12 title:
13 1. "Competent" or "competency" means the present ability of a
14 person arrested for or charged with a crime to understand the nature
15 of the charges and proceedings brought against him or her and to
16 effectively and rationally assist in his or her defense;
17 2. "Criminal proceeding" means every stage of a criminal
18 prosecution after arrest and before judgment, including, but not
19 limited to, interrogation, lineup, preliminary hearing, motion
20 dockets, discovery, pretrial hearings and trial;
21 3. "Dangerous" means a person who is a person requiring
22 treatment as defined in Section 1-103 of Title 43A of the Oklahoma
23 Statutes;
24
Req. No. 16517 Page 2

1 4. "Incompetent" or "incompetency" means the present inability
2 of a person arrested for or charged with a crime to understand the
3 nature of the charges and proceedings brought against him or her and
4 to effectively and rationally assist in his or her defense;
5 5. "Public guardian" means the Office of Public Guardian as
6 established under the Oklahoma Public Guardianship Act in Section 6-
7 101 et seq. of Title 30 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
8 6. "Qualified forensic examiner evaluator" means any:
9 a. psychiatrist with forensic training and experience,
10 b. psychologist with forensic training and experience, or
11 c. a licensed mental health professional whose forensic
12 training and experience enable him or her to form
13 expert opinions regarding mental illness, competency
14 and dangerousness and who has been approved to render
15 such opinions by the court; provided, however, a
16 licensed mental health professional shall not be
17 qualified to issue expert opinions as to competency or
18 dangerousness in cases in which a person is alleged to
19 be incompetent due to intellectual disability; and
20 7. "Reasonable period of time" means a period not to exceed the
21 lesser of:
22 a. the maximum sentence specified for the most serious
23 offense with which the defendant is charged, or
24 b. a maximum period of two (2) years.
Req. No. 16517 Page 3

1 Any time period where the defendant refuses medication
2 prescribed or ordered that is designed to restore the defendant to
3 competency shall not be used in the calculation of a reasonable
4 period of time.
5 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 22 O.S. 2021, Section 1175.3, as
6 amended by Section 2, Chapter 73, O.S.L. 2024 (22 O.S. Supp. 2025,
7 Section 1175.3), is amended to read as follows:
8 Section 1175.3. A. Upon filing of an application for
9 determination of competency, the court shall set a hearing date,
10 which shall be as soon as practicable, but at least one (1) day
11 after service of notice as provided by Section 1175.2 of this title.
12 B. The court shall hold a hearing on the date provided. At the
13 hearing, the court shall examine the application for determination
14 of competency to determine if it alleges facts sufficient to raise a
15 doubt as to the competency of the person. Any additional evidence
16 tending to create a doubt as to the competency of the person may be
17 presented at this hearing.
18 C. If the court finds there is no doubt as to the competency of
19 the person, it shall order the criminal proceedings to resume.
20 D. 1. a. If the court finds there is a doubt as to the
21 competency of the person, it shall order the person to
22 be examined evaluated by the Department of Mental
23 Health and Substance Abuse Services or by a qualified
24 forensic examiner evaluator designated by the
Req. No. 16517 Page 4

1 Department to perform competency examinations
2 evaluations.
3 b. In addition, the Developmental Disabilities Services
4 Division and the Office of Public Guardian of the
5 Department of Human Services shall receive written
6 notice from the district attorney who filed the
7 criminal petition, and be authorized by order of the
8 court to have a psychologist or other appropriate
9 clinician participate with professionals assigned by
10 any other public or private agency in any competency
11 evaluation where developmental or intellectual
12 disability may be involved. The psychologist or
13 clinician employed, by contract or otherwise, by the
14 Department of Human Services may issue a separate
15 opinion and recommendation to the court. In such
16 cases where intellectual disability may be involved,
17 the Office of Public Guardian shall have standing to
18 participate in any stage of the proceedings as deemed
19 necessary by the Office.
20 2. The person shall be examined evaluated by a qualified
21 forensic examiner evaluator on an outpatient basis prior to referral
22 for any necessary inpatient evaluation, as ordered by the court.
23 The outpatient examination evaluation may be conducted in the
24 community, the jail or detention facility where the person is held.
Req. No. 16517 Page 5

1 3. If the court determines that the person whose competency is
2 in question may be dangerous as defined in Section 1175.1 of this
3 title, it shall order the person retained in a secure facility until
4 the completion of the competency hearing provided in Section 1175.4
5 of this title. If the court determines the person may be dangerous
6 as defined in Section 1175.1 of this title because the individual is
7 a person requiring treatment as defined in Section 1-103 of Title
8 43A of the Oklahoma Statutes, it may commit the person to the
9 custody of the Department of Mental Health and Substance Abuse
10 Services or any other state agency or private facility for the
11 examination evaluation required by this subsection. The person
12 shall be required to undergo examination evaluation for a period of
13 time sufficient for the qualified forensic examiner evaluator or
14 examiners evaluators to reach a conclusion as to competency, and the
15 court shall impose a reasonable time limitation for such period of
16 examination evaluation.
17 E. The qualified forensic examiner evaluator or examiners
18 evaluators shall receive instructions that they shall examine
19 evaluate the patient person to determine:
20 1. If the person is able to appreciate the nature of the
21 charges made against such person;
22 2. If the person is able to consult with the lawyer and
23 rationally assist in the preparation of the defense of such person;
24
Req. No. 16517 Page 6

1 3. If the person is unable to appreciate the nature of the
2 charges or to consult and rationally assist in the preparation of
3 the defense, whether the person can attain competency within a
4 reasonable period of time as defined in Section 1175.1 of this title
5 if provided with a course of treatment, therapy or training;
6 4. If the person is a person requiring treatment as defined by
7 Section 1-103 of Title 43A of the Oklahoma Statutes;
8 5. If the person is incompetent because the person is
9 intellectually disabled as defined in Section 1408 of Title 10 of
10 the Oklahoma Statutes;
11 6. If the requirements of paragraphs 4 and 5 of this subsection
12 are not established, the reasoning for which the defendant is
13 otherwise incompetent; and
14 7. If the person were released, whether such person would
15 presently be dangerous as defined in Section 1175.1 of this title.
16 F. Upon completion of the competency evaluation, the Department
17 of Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services or qualified forensic
18 examiner evaluator designated by the Department to perform
19 competency examinations evaluations shall notify the court of its
20 findings. If the person is in the custody of the Department of
21 Mental Health and Substance Abuse Services, the person shall be
22 returned to the court in the customary manner within five (5)
23 business days. If the person is not returned within that time, the
24 county in which the proceedings are to be held shall pay the costs
Req. No. 16517 Page 7

1 of m aintaining the person at the institution or facility for the
2 period of time the person remains at the institution or facility in
3 excess of the five-day period.
4 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 22 O.S. 2021, Section 1175.4, as
5 amended by Section 3, Chapter 73, O.S.L. 2024 (22 O.S. Supp. 2025,
6 Section 1175.4), is amended to read as follows:
7 Section 1175.4. A. A hearing to determine the competency of
8 the person whose competency is in question shall be held within
9 thirty (30) days after the qualified forensic examiner evaluator or
10 examiners evaluators have made the determination required in Section
11 1175.3 of this title. In such cases where intellectual disability
12 may be involved, the Office of Public Guardian shall have standing
13 to participate in any stage of the proceedings as deemed necessary
14 by the Office.
15 B. The court, at the hearing, shall determine by a
16 preponderance of the evidence if the person is incompetent. Such
17 determination shall include consideration of all reports prepared by
18 the qualified forensic examiner evaluator or examiners evaluators;
19 provided, however, in any case where intellectual disability may be
20 involved, the recommendations of examiners evaluators set forth in
21 subparagraph b of paragraph 1 of subsection D of Section 1175.3 of
22 this title shall be considered by the court. The person shall be
23 presumed to be competent for the purposes of the allocation of the
24 burden of proof and burden of going forward with the evidence. If
Req. No. 16517 Page 8

1 the court deems it necessary, or if the person alleged to be a
2 person requiring treatment, or any relative, friend, or any person
3 with whom he may reside, or at whose house the person may be, shall
4 so demand, the court shall schedule the hearing on the application
5 as a jury trial to be held within seventy-two (72) hours of the
6 request, excluding weekends and legal holidays, or within as much
7 additional time as is requested by the attorney of the person whose
8 competency is in question, upon good cause shown. The jury shall be
9 composed of six (6) persons having the qualifications required of
10 jurors in courts of record, summoned to determine the questions of
11 the person's competency of the person and need for treatment.
12 Whenever a jury is required, the court shall proceed to the
13 selection of such jury in the manner as provided by law and such
14 jury shall determine the questions of the competency and need for
15 treatment of the person whose competency is in question. The jurors
16 shall receive fees for attendance and mileage as are allowed by law.
17 C. The person whose competency is in question shall have the
18 right to be present at the hearing on the petition unless it is made
19 to appear to the court that the presence of the person makes it
20 impossible to conduct the hearing in a reasonable manner. The court
21 may not decide in advance of the hearing, solely on the basis of the
22 certificate of the examining doctor or doctors qualified forensic
23 evaluator, that the person whose competency is in question should
24 not be allowed to appear. It shall be made to appear to the court
Req. No. 16517 Page 9

1 base d on clear and convincing evidence that alternatives to
2 exclusion were attempted before the court renders the person's
3 removal of the person for that purpose or the person's appearance of
4 the person at such hearing improper and unsafe.
5 D. All witnesses shall be subject to cross-examination in the
6 same manner as is provided by law. If so stipulated by counsel for
7 a person whose competency is in question, the district attorney and
8 the court, testimony may be given by telephone or other electronic
9 transmitting device approved by the court. No statement, admission
10 or confession made by the person whose competency is in question
11 obtained during the examination evaluation for competency may be
12 used for any purpose except for proceedings under Section 1175.1 et
13 seq. of this title. No such statement, admission or confession may
14 be used against such person in any criminal action whether pending
15 at the time the hearing is held or filed against such person at any
16 later time, directly, indirectly or in any manner or form.
17 E. If the question of competency is submitted to a jury, the
18 court shall instruct the jury as to the law regarding competency,
19 and the findings they are to make. If the trial of the question is
20 to the court, the court shall make the required findings.
